title.narrative: ACCESS TO INTEGRATED SOCIAL SERVICES, INCLUDING IN HUMANITARIAN SETTINGS

description.narrative: By 2022, vulnerable families with children and those with children with delays and disabilities have access to social services in selected communities, including in humanitarian settings, which contributes to Cross Sectoral - Children With Disabilities, Cross-Sectoral - Social And Behaviour Change, Cross-Sectoral - Social And Behaviour Change (Covid), Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect (Covid), Reducing Child Poverty. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, the most vulnerable children in Ukraine benefit from more-child-friendly and family-oriented social welfare and justice systems.

description.narrative: Vulnerable families with children including IDPs continue to have limited access to social services, especially in Eastern Ukraine. Through humanitarian, recovery and development programmes, UNICEF ;enhanced ;the capacity of professionals and caregivers on child protection issues and ensured child and family-centered services. In 2021, the child protection humanitarian program reached around 45,500 children and caregivers with psycho-social and child protection activities. ;Child welfare- related tools and best practice models developed on integrated social services wereare documented and shared with the Ministry of Social Policy and other national stakeholders for further replication under the on-going decentralization reforms.; | Status:On-track | As-of Date:24/01/2022
